                type="document" xml:id="d327">
                <head>327. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On April 2, 1965, Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_PLB1">Pearson</persName>,
                    in an address at Temple University in Philadelphia, suggested changes in U.S.
                    policy in the Vietnam conflict. President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1"
                        >Johnson</persName> invited <persName corresp="#p_PLB1">Pearson</persName>
                    to meet with him the following day at Camp <persName>David</persName>, Maryland.
                    According to the President’s Daily Diary, the meeting was held between 12:30 and
                    2:45 p.m. (Johnson Library) No U.S. record of the discussions between the two
                    men was found. At an April 22 press conference in Ottawa, <persName
                        corresp="#p_PLB1">Pearson</persName> confirmed reports that the meeting with
                    the President centered on the question of Vietnam and had been acrimonious but
                    insisted that they had parted on good terms. <persName corresp="#p_PLB1"
                        >Pearson</persName>’s account of the meeting is in <hi rend="italic">Mike:
                        Memoirs of the Right Honorable <persName corresp="#p_PLB1">Lester B.
                            Pearson</persName>
                    </hi>, Volume 3, pages 138-142. Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_RCSA1">Charles
                        Ritchie</persName>, who was also present at Camp <persName>David</persName>,
                    commented on the meeting in Storm Signals, pages 80-83.</p>
            </div>
